# Day 05 - Delete from Beginning (Singly Linked List)

## Definition

Deleting from the beginning means removing the first node of the linked list and making the second node the new head.

Example:

Before:

10 -> 20 -> 30 -> 40 -> NULL

After Deletion:

20 -> 30 -> 40 -> NULL

---

## Algorithm

1. Check if the linked list is empty.
2. If empty, return `null`.
3. Move the head to the next node.
4. Return the updated head.

---

## Syntax

```java
if (head == null) {
    return null;
}

head = head.next;

return head;
```

---

## Dry Run

Initial List:

Head
 |
 ▼
10 -> 20 -> 30 -> 40 -> NULL

Step 1:

```java
head = head.next;
```

Now:

Head
 |
 ▼
20 -> 30 -> 40 -> NULL

The node containing `10` is no longer referenced.

---

## Time Complexity

| Operation | Complexity |
|-----------|------------|
| Delete from Beginning | O(1) |

Reason:

No traversal is required. Only one reference (`head`) is updated.

---

## Space Complexity

| Operation | Complexity |
|-----------|------------|
| Extra Space | O(1) |

---

## Key Points

- `head` always points to the first node.
- After deletion, `head` points to the second node.
- If there is only one node, `head` becomes `null`.
- Java automatically removes unreachable nodes using Garbage Collection.
- No manual memory deallocation is required.

---

## Common Mistakes

### ❌ Wrong

```java
head.next = head;
```

This creates an incorrect link and does not delete the first node.

### ✅ Correct

```java
head = head.next;
```

